<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<FindBugsFilter xmlns="https://github.com/spotbugs/filter/3.0.0">
  <!--
    Reviewed suppressions (Chapter 16: suppress with a reason, never disable a whole detector).

    This module ships ONE deliberate counter-example whose contract violation IS the lesson, so a test
    can prove the failure the prose describes rather than merely assert it. The detectors are left
    fully ENABLED for the rest of the module (the encapsulated Order, the value types, both services
    all stay clean); only the named counter-example class carries a finding, suppressed narrowly, with
    a reason, and pointed at the test that demonstrates why it matters. Fixing the class — which Order
    already does — is the real advice; the suppression exists only so the teaching counter-example can
    ship green.
  -->

  <!--
    OrderLeaky returns its internal list directly, so a caller can mutate the order through the returned
    reference — the chapter's worked smell that is also a latent mutation bug. At this module's
    threshold SpotBugs raises EI_EXPOSE_REP on the lines() accessor (verified: the finding fires here,
    so the suppression is load-bearing, not decorative); EI_EXPOSE_REP2 is matched too as the related
    store-side pattern in case a stricter threshold raises it. Proven by
    CodeSmellsTest#leakedListMutationCorruptsTheOrder. The fix is the defensive copy in Order's compact
    constructor (List.copyOf), never this suppression.
  -->
  <Match>
    <Class name="org.acme.smells.OrderLeaky"/>
    <Bug pattern="EI_EXPOSE_REP,EI_EXPOSE_REP2"/>
  </Match>
</FindBugsFilter>
